      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "03b148b022057492",
      "text": "The heights of wildfire smoke plumes are a complex function of the wildfire heat flux, fire geometry, and the ambient meteorological profile. While a weak correlation exists between the fire intensity and plume top height, atmospheric stability acts to limit the buoyant plume rise by inducing plume injection/smoke detrainment."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7d4d02b69c5785e0",
      "text": "As the plume rises, environmental eddies entrain cold air into the plume, diluting the vertical momentum and therefore limiting the plume top height. The effects of dynamic entrainment, produced by a strong horizontal wind, result in a bent-over plume structure. Furthermore, latent heat release offers a means to fuel additional plume rise, highlighting the importance of moist layers and moist convection to plume top height."
